document:
**Security Rule:** Authorization decisions must flow through a single, well-tested component or policy layer rather than being re-implemented inline at each call site, so the rules stay consistent and auditable.

**Vulnerability Pattern (Description):** Each endpoint hand-codes its own role and permission checks, so the logic drifts between handlers, a new endpoint silently ships with no check, and a rule change has to be found and applied in many places.

**Secure Pattern (Description):** A shared authorization service, decorator, middleware, or policy object evaluates every access decision against one rule set, so all endpoints enforce the same logic and an added endpoint inherits it.

[[C# PATTERNS]]
Vulnerable:
```
public IActionResult Delete(int id) {
  if (!User.IsInRole("Admin")) return Forbid();
}
```
Secure:
```
[Authorize(Policy = "post:delete")]
public IActionResult Delete(int id) { ... }
```

[[GENERIC PATTERNS]]
Vulnerable:
```
def handler(req): if req.user.role == "editor" or req.user.role == "admin": ...
```
Secure:
```
@requires_permission("article:edit")
def handler(req): ...
```

[[JAVA PATTERNS]]
Vulnerable:
```
public void delete(Long id) {
  if (!user.getRole().equals("ADMIN")) throw new ForbiddenException();
}
```
Secure:
```
@PreAuthorize("hasAuthority('post:delete')")
public void delete(Long id) { ... }
```

[[JAVASCRIPT PATTERNS]]
Vulnerable:
```
app.delete("/posts/:id", (req, res) => {
  if (req.user.role !== "admin") return res.sendStatus(403);
});
```
Secure:
```
app.delete("/posts/:id", requirePermission("post:delete"), handler);
```

[[PYTHON PATTERNS]]
Vulnerable:
```
@app.put("/articles/{id}")
def update(id, user=Depends(current_user)):
    if user.role not in ("editor", "admin"):
        raise HTTPException(403)
```
Secure:
```
@app.put("/articles/{id}")
def update(id, _=Depends(require_permission("article:edit"))):
    ...
```

**Security Rule:** When an authorization check throws an error, times out, or returns an indeterminate result, the system must treat that outcome as a denial rather than allowing the request to proceed.

**Vulnerability Pattern (Description):** An exception in the permission check is swallowed, or a catch block falls through, leaving execution to continue past the gate as though access had been granted.

**Secure Pattern (Description):** Any error or ambiguous result from the authorization path is caught and converted into an explicit denial before the protected operation is reached.

[[C# PATTERNS]]
Vulnerable:
```
bool allowed;
try { allowed = _policy.Check(user, res); }
catch { allowed = true; }
```
Secure:
```
bool allowed = false;
try { allowed = _policy.Check(user, res); }
catch { allowed = false; }
```

[[GENERIC PATTERNS]]
Vulnerable:
```
try: allowed = check(user, res)
except: pass            # allowed stays whatever it was
```
Secure:
```
try: allowed = check(user, res)
except: allowed = false
```

[[JAVA PATTERNS]]
Vulnerable:
```
boolean allowed;
try { allowed = policy.check(user, res); }
catch (Exception e) { allowed = true; }
```
Secure:
```
boolean allowed = false;
try { allowed = policy.check(user, res); }
catch (Exception e) { allowed = false; }
```

[[JAVASCRIPT PATTERNS]]
Vulnerable:
```
let allowed;
try { allowed = await checkAccess(user, res); }
catch (e) { allowed = true; }
```
Secure:
```
let allowed = false;
try { allowed = await checkAccess(user, res); }
catch (e) { allowed = false; }
```

[[PYTHON PATTERNS]]
Vulnerable:
```
try:
    authorized = policy.evaluate(user, resource)
except PolicyError:
    authorized = True
```
Secure:
```
try:
    authorized = policy.evaluate(user, resource)
except PolicyError:
    authorized = False
```

**Security Rule:** Failed authorization attempts must be logged with the caller identity, the resource, and the action so that probing, privilege escalation attempts, and broken-access-control abuse are detectable.

**Vulnerability Pattern (Description):** A denied request is rejected silently with only an error response, so a user systematically enumerating resources or roles leaves no trail for monitoring or alerting to act on.

**Secure Pattern (Description):** Every authorization denial emits a structured security log event recording who was denied, what they tried to reach, and the action, feeding detection and alerting.

[[C# PATTERNS]]
Vulnerable:
```
if (!allowed) return Forbid();
```
Secure:
```
if (!allowed) {
  _logger.LogWarning("authz_denied user={User} resource={Res} action={Act}",
      user.Id, resourceId, action);
  return Forbid();
}
```

[[GENERIC PATTERNS]]
Vulnerable:
```
if not allowed: return deny()
```
Secure:
```
if not allowed:
    securityLog.warn("authz_denied", user=user.id, resource=res, action=act)
    return deny()
```

[[JAVA PATTERNS]]
Vulnerable:
```
if (!allowed) throw new ForbiddenException();
```
Secure:
```
if (!allowed) {
  securityLog.warn("authz_denied user={} resource={} action={}",
      user.getId(), resourceId, action);
  throw new ForbiddenException();
}
```

[[JAVASCRIPT PATTERNS]]
Vulnerable:
```
if (!allowed) return res.sendStatus(403);
```
Secure:
```
if (!allowed) {
  logger.warn({ event: "authz_denied", user: user.id, resource, action });
  return res.sendStatus(403);
}
```

[[PYTHON PATTERNS]]
Vulnerable:
```
if not authorized:
    raise HTTPException(403)
```
Secure:
```
if not authorized:
    log.warning("authz_denied user=%s resource=%s action=%s",
                user.id, resource_id, action)
    raise HTTPException(403)
```

**Security Rule:** When an operation errors, times out, or reaches an unexpected state, the system must fall back to a denied and safe condition rather than granting access or continuing as if the operation had succeeded.

**Vulnerability Pattern (Description):** An exception or timeout in a security check is caught and treated as success, or a default branch grants access, so a failure in the control becomes an open door instead of a closed one.

**Secure Pattern (Description):** Security decisions default to deny — an unhandled state, an exception, or a timeout in an authorization or validation step results in the request being rejected and the error logged.

[[C# PATTERNS]]
Vulnerable:
```
bool ok;
try { ok = _authz.Check(user, res); } catch { ok = true; }
```
Secure:
```
bool ok = false;
try { ok = _authz.Check(user, res); }
catch (Exception e) { _log.LogError(e, "authz failure"); }
```

[[GENERIC PATTERNS]]
Vulnerable:
```
try: allowed = authz.check(user, resource)
except: allowed = true            # error opens access
```
Secure:
```
try: allowed = authz.check(user, resource)
except: allowed = false           # error denies access
```

[[JAVA PATTERNS]]
Vulnerable:
```
boolean granted;
try { granted = acl.permit(user, res); }
catch (Exception e) { granted = true; }
```
Secure:
```
boolean granted = false;
try { granted = acl.permit(user, res); }
catch (Exception e) { log.error("acl failure", e); }
```

[[JAVASCRIPT PATTERNS]]
Vulnerable:
```
let ok;
try { ok = await verifyToken(t); } catch { ok = true; }
```
Secure:
```
let ok = false;
try { ok = await verifyToken(t); } catch (e) { logger.error(e); }
```

[[PYTHON PATTERNS]]
Vulnerable:
```
def is_allowed(user, doc):
    try:
        return policy.evaluate(user, doc)
    except Exception:
        return True               # fails open
```
Secure:
```
def is_allowed(user, doc):
    try:
        return policy.evaluate(user, doc)
    except Exception:
        log.exception("authz error")
        return False              # fails closed
```

**Security Rule:** Unhandled errors must return a generic message to the client by default while full diagnostic detail is written only to server-side logs, so internal paths, queries, and versions are never leaked.

**Vulnerability Pattern (Description):** An exception handler returns the exception message, stack trace, or SQL fragment in the HTTP response, revealing internal structure that helps an attacker target the system.

**Secure Pattern (Description):** A global error handler logs the full exception with a correlation id server-side and returns only a generic message and that id to the client.

[[C# PATTERNS]]
Vulnerable:
```
catch (Exception ex) { return StatusCode(500, ex.ToString()); }
```
Secure:
```
catch (Exception ex) {
    _logger.LogError(ex, "request failed");
    return StatusCode(500, "Internal server error");
}
```

[[GENERIC PATTERNS]]
Vulnerable:
```
respond(500, str(exception))      # raw exception sent to client
```
Secure:
```
log.error(exception); respond(500, "An unexpected error occurred")
```

[[JAVA PATTERNS]]
Vulnerable:
```
catch (Exception e) {
    return ResponseEntity.status(500).body(e.toString());
}
```
Secure:
```
catch (Exception e) {
    log.error("request failed", e);
    return ResponseEntity.status(500).body("Internal server error");
}
```

[[JAVASCRIPT PATTERNS]]
Vulnerable:
```
app.use((err, req, res, n) => res.status(500).send(err.stack));
```
Secure:
```
app.use((err, req, res, n) => {
    logger.error(err);
    res.status(500).json({ error: "Internal server error" });
});
```

[[PYTHON PATTERNS]]
Vulnerable:
```
except Exception as e:
    return jsonify({"error": str(e)}), 500
```
Secure:
```
except Exception as e:
    app.logger.exception(e)
    return jsonify({"error": "Internal server error"}), 500
```

**Security Rule:** Security-relevant events such as authentication successes and failures, access-control denials, input-validation failures, and privilege changes must be logged so incidents can be detected and investigated.

**Vulnerability Pattern (Description):** Authentication, authorization, and other security-relevant outcomes happen silently, so a failed login burst, a privilege escalation, or an access denial leaves no record and goes unnoticed.

**Secure Pattern (Description):** Every security-relevant decision emits a structured log event that records the actor, the action, the outcome, and enough context to support detection and investigation.

[[C# PATTERNS]]
Vulnerable:
```
if (!await _signIn.PasswordSignInAsync(user, pw, false, false).Succeeded)
    return Unauthorized();
```
Secure:
```
if (!(await _signIn.PasswordSignInAsync(user, pw, false, false)).Succeeded) {
    _logger.LogWarning("auth.login.failure user={User} ip={Ip}", user, ip);
    return Unauthorized();
}
```

[[GENERIC PATTERNS]]
Vulnerable:
```
if not check_password(user, pw):
    return error("invalid credentials")     # silent failure
```
Secure:
```
if not check_password(user, pw):
    log.warning("auth.login.failure", user=user.id, ip=client_ip)
    return error("invalid credentials")
```

[[JAVA PATTERNS]]
Vulnerable:
```
if (!authService.login(username, password)) {
    return Response.status(401).build();
}
```
Secure:
```
if (!authService.login(username, password)) {
    log.warn("auth.login.failure user={} ip={}", username, request.getRemoteAddr());
    return Response.status(401).build();
}
```

[[JAVASCRIPT PATTERNS]]
Vulnerable:
```
if (!user) return res.status(401).end();
```
Secure:
```
if (!user) {
  logger.warn("auth.login.failure", { username, ip: req.ip });
  return res.status(401).end();
}
```

[[PYTHON PATTERNS]]
Vulnerable:
```
if not authenticate(username, password):
    raise HTTPException(401)
```
Secure:
```
if not authenticate(username, password):
    logger.warning("auth.login.failure user=%s ip=%s", username, request.client.host)
    raise HTTPException(401)
```

**Security Rule:** The address that is validated must be the exact address the request connects to, so a name cannot resolve to a safe address during the check and to an internal address when the request is made.

**Vulnerability Pattern (Description):** The hostname is resolved once for validation and resolved again for the connection, so a time-of-check to time-of-use DNS rebinding swaps a public answer for an internal one between the two lookups.

**Secure Pattern (Description):** The hostname is resolved a single time, the returned address is validated, and that same pinned address is used to open the connection so the check cannot be bypassed.

[[C# PATTERNS]]
Vulnerable:
```
if (IsPublic((await Dns.GetHostAddressesAsync(host))[0]))
    await httpClient.GetAsync("https://" + host);
```
Secure:
```
var ip = (await Dns.GetHostAddressesAsync(host))[0];
if (!IsPublic(ip)) throw new InvalidOperationException();
var req = new HttpRequestMessage(HttpMethod.Get, $"https://{ip}/");
req.Headers.Host = host;
await httpClient.SendAsync(req);
```

[[GENERIC PATTERNS]]
Vulnerable:
```
if isPublic(resolve(host)): httpGet("https://" + host)
```
Secure:
```
ip = resolve(host)
if isPublic(ip): httpGetToAddress(ip, host)
```

[[JAVA PATTERNS]]
Vulnerable:
```
if (isPublic(InetAddress.getByName(host)))
    new URL("https://" + host).openConnection();
```
Secure:
```
InetAddress addr = InetAddress.getByName(host);
if (!isPublic(addr)) throw new SecurityException();
var conn = new URL("https", addr.getHostAddress(), "/").openConnection();
conn.setRequestProperty("Host", host);
```

[[JAVASCRIPT PATTERNS]]
Vulnerable:
```
if (isPublic((await dns.promises.lookup(host)).address))
    await fetch("https://" + host);
```
Secure:
```
const { address } = await dns.promises.lookup(host);
if (!isPublic(address)) throw new Error("private ip");
await fetch(`https://${address}`, { headers: { Host: host } });
```

[[PYTHON PATTERNS]]
Vulnerable:
```
if is_public(socket.gethostbyname(host)):
    requests.get("https://" + host)
```
Secure:
```
ip = socket.gethostbyname(host)
if not is_public(ip): abort(400)
requests.get(f"https://{ip}", headers={"Host": host}, verify=host)
```

**Security Rule:** Untrusted URLs must be parsed and normalized with a robust URL parser before validation, so credentials, encoded characters, and confusing authority syntax cannot smuggle a different host past the check.

**Vulnerability Pattern (Description):** A URL is validated with string matching on the raw input, so embedded credentials, an at sign, encoded characters, or an unexpected port let the real connect host differ from the host that was checked.

**Secure Pattern (Description):** The URL is parsed by a standards-compliant parser, the normalized host and port are extracted, and validation runs against those parsed components rather than the raw string.

[[C# PATTERNS]]
Vulnerable:
```
if (userUrl.StartsWith("https://api.example.com"))
    await httpClient.GetAsync(userUrl);
```
Secure:
```
var u = new Uri(userUrl);
if (u.Host == "api.example.com" && u.Port == 443)
    await httpClient.GetAsync(u);
```

[[GENERIC PATTERNS]]
Vulnerable:
```
if userUrl.startsWith("https://api.example.com"): fetch(userUrl)
```
Secure:
```
u = parseUrl(userUrl)
if u.host == "api.example.com" and u.port in {443, none}: fetch(u)
```

[[JAVA PATTERNS]]
Vulnerable:
```
if (userUrl.startsWith("https://api.example.com"))
    new URL(userUrl).openConnection();
```
Secure:
```
URI u = URI.create(userUrl).normalize();
if ("api.example.com".equals(u.getHost()) && (u.getPort() == -1 || u.getPort() == 443))
    u.toURL().openConnection();
```

[[JAVASCRIPT PATTERNS]]
Vulnerable:
```
if (userUrl.startsWith("https://api.example.com")) await fetch(userUrl);
```
Secure:
```
const u = new URL(userUrl);
if (u.hostname === "api.example.com" && (u.port === "" || u.port === "443"))
    await fetch(u);
```

[[PYTHON PATTERNS]]
Vulnerable:
```
if user_url.startswith("https://api.example.com"):
    requests.get(user_url)
```
Secure:
```
u = urlparse(user_url)
if u.hostname == "api.example.com" and u.port in (None, 443):
    requests.get(user_url)
```
